      "learned": "Salts are ionic compounds formed when the hydrogen atom(s) in an acid are fully or partially replaced by a positive ion (a metal ion or ammonium ion). There are four types: (1) Normal salts — all replaceable hydrogen replaced, e.g., NaCl, ZnSO₄, CAN (NH₄NO₃·Ca(NO₃)₂); (2) Acid salts — hydrogen only partially replaced, e.g., NaHCO₃, NaHSO₄; (3) Basic salts — contain an OH⁻ group alongside the salt anion, e.g., Pb(OH)Cl; (4) Double salts — contain two different cations or anions, e.g., potash alum KAl(SO₄)₂·12H₂O. Students learn to name salts from parent acids (hydrochloric → chloride; sulphuric → sulphate; nitric → nitrate; carbonic → carbonate; phosphoric → phosphate).",
